00:12:06.170 --> 00:12:08.150
So it just helps
for their tuition.

00:12:08.150 --> 00:12:09.658
RAJ AJRAWAT: OK, that's great.

00:12:09.658 --> 00:12:11.200
Yeah, so I mean, I
think that there's

00:12:11.200 --> 00:12:13.617
a lot of these different things
to think about when you're

00:12:13.617 --> 00:12:16.330
obviously trying to sell
your specific service

00:12:16.330 --> 00:12:18.010
to these markets.

00:12:18.010 --> 00:12:20.145
I'd like to potentially
now transition

00:12:20.145 --> 00:12:21.520
to some of these
technical issues

00:12:21.520 --> 00:12:24.040
that a lot of our partners face.

00:12:24.040 --> 00:12:27.250
And actually, we were
talking previously,

00:12:27.250 --> 00:12:30.020
the panel, that even
size can be a big issue.

00:12:30.020 --> 00:12:33.790
So Jim, walk us through
some of the technical things

00:12:33.790 --> 00:12:36.100
that you had to think
about before you approached

00:12:36.100 --> 00:12:38.980
the market, or also
just technical issues

00:12:38.980 --> 00:12:41.443
that you might have
encountered after you entered.

00:12:41.443 --> 00:12:43.360
JIM STERN: That we were
surprised about later.

00:12:43.360 --> 00:12:45.060
RAJ AJRAWAT: Right, that
you were surprised about it.

00:12:45.060 --> 00:12:46.360
How did you react to them?

00:12:46.360 --> 00:12:48.610
How did you guys
build in flex to be

00:12:48.610 --> 00:12:52.790
able to address those issues
for your users as well?

00:12:52.790 --> 00:12:55.600
JIM STERN: So we had a couple
of different things going

00:12:55.600 --> 00:12:58.190
on with a few of our games.

00:12:58.190 --> 00:13:01.660
So in the case of Okey
that I was talking about,

00:13:01.660 --> 00:13:04.090
it's predominantly
played in Turkey.

00:13:04.090 --> 00:13:08.690
And the closest AWS server that
we could get was in Germany.

00:13:08.690 --> 00:13:10.720
So there was some
latency issues--

00:13:10.720 --> 00:13:11.750
not horrible.

00:13:11.750 --> 00:13:13.690
But we were able to
find servers that

00:13:13.690 --> 00:13:16.870
were local within Turkey
that were price-competitive

00:13:16.870 --> 00:13:19.360
as well, that actually
were much better in terms

00:13:19.360 --> 00:13:20.390
of the latency issue.

00:13:20.390 --> 00:13:23.570
So we were able to hook
them up over there.

00:13:23.570 --> 00:13:27.010
We've also had situations
like with Poker

00:13:27.010 --> 00:13:29.230
where we thought, OK,
this is a global game how

00:13:29.230 --> 00:13:32.870
do we target the particular
emerging markets?

00:13:32.870 --> 00:13:36.130
Let's segment the
servers based off

00:13:36.130 --> 00:13:38.380
of the different languages
of the different countries

00:13:38.380 --> 00:13:39.850
where the people are playing.

00:13:39.850 --> 00:13:42.940
And we found that actually
had an issue on liquidity,

00:13:42.940 --> 00:13:46.180
that people weren't able to
find other players because they

00:13:46.180 --> 00:13:47.740
were on different servers.

00:13:47.740 --> 00:13:50.320
So to accommodate for
that, we put everybody back

00:13:50.320 --> 00:13:53.090
into a single set
of servers again.

00:13:53.090 --> 00:13:56.650
And in order to customize
the game for them,

00:13:56.650 --> 00:14:00.753
we tried to give them
customized events

00:14:00.753 --> 00:14:02.920
that we would customize for
that particular culture,

00:14:02.920 --> 00:14:04.295
but then make
something else that

00:14:04.295 --> 00:14:07.930
was a little bit more generic
for the rest of the world.

00:14:07.930 --> 00:14:12.970
And then in the case of Rangoli
Rekha, which is a match 3

00:14:12.970 --> 00:14:16.810
game that we did in India,
it was very important

00:14:16.810 --> 00:14:18.910
that we knew the customer base.

00:14:18.910 --> 00:14:20.920
So it's predominantly Android.

00:14:20.920 --> 00:14:23.530
So we focused on Android.

00:14:23.530 --> 00:14:27.640
They don't have the
same access to Wi-Fi,

00:14:27.640 --> 00:14:30.150
so we had to make sure that
the file size was down,

00:14:30.150 --> 00:14:32.780
so we kept it 20 megs.

00:14:32.780 --> 00:14:35.500
And based on the research
that we had done,

00:14:35.500 --> 00:14:38.050
we found that up to
40% of the people

00:14:38.050 --> 00:14:42.160
find other fileshare servers
to go to download the game.

00:14:42.160 --> 00:14:45.370
So we made sure it was
accessible through services

00:14:45.370 --> 00:14:48.820
like FireShare in
order for them to be

00:14:48.820 --> 00:14:50.650
able to download their games.

00:14:50.650 --> 00:14:52.150
RAJ AJRAWAT: Now,
Mark, did you guys

00:14:52.150 --> 00:14:54.400
have any similar issues around
size or anything like that?

00:14:54.400 --> 00:14:56.067
Or is that a consideration
for you guys?

00:14:56.067 --> 00:14:58.420
JIM STERN: It's definitely
a huge consideration.

00:14:58.420 --> 00:15:03.130
So four years ago, when Marvin
Contest of Champions launched,

00:15:03.130 --> 00:15:05.315
players actually had
to be on Wi-Fi in order

00:15:05.315 --> 00:15:06.190
to download the game.

00:15:06.190 --> 00:15:07.700
The game is huge.

00:15:07.700 --> 00:15:11.860
I would probably say, on device,
it's around like 700 megabytes.

00:15:11.860 --> 00:15:14.110
So you can see that could
be a hurdle for acquisition.

00:15:14.110 --> 00:15:18.190
So shortly after that, we had to
quickly pivot our central tech

00:15:18.190 --> 00:15:19.460
strategy.

00:15:19.460 --> 00:15:21.550
So what we did is we
made our initial download

00:15:21.550 --> 00:15:22.960
sub-100 megabytes.

00:15:22.960 --> 00:15:25.210
And what that did for
us is it enabled players

00:15:25.210 --> 00:15:28.300
to download the
game over cellular.

00:15:28.300 --> 00:15:30.377
And while they're playing
through the tutorial,

00:15:30.377 --> 00:15:31.960
our game leverages
on-demand resources

00:15:31.960 --> 00:15:33.920
to download the
rest of the package.

00:15:33.920 --> 00:15:36.270
So not only did we
see optimization

00:15:36.270 --> 00:15:38.200
in our yields and
our CPIs, but also it

00:15:38.200 --> 00:15:40.980
made our game more accessible
in the emerging markets where

00:15:40.980 --> 00:15:43.680
the infrastructure wasn't
really fully developed

00:15:43.680 --> 00:15:45.697
and Wi-Fi wasn't
readily available.

00:15:45.697 --> 00:15:47.280
RAJ AJRAWAT: Yeah,
and I mean, I think

00:15:47.280 --> 00:15:49.738
that highlights a lot of what
we were talking about earlier

00:15:49.738 --> 00:15:53.790
today, when you saw Dom up here
on stage, why we're so focused

00:15:53.790 --> 00:15:55.530
on size reduction.

00:15:55.530 --> 00:15:57.570
You can see the
benefits around actually

00:15:57.570 --> 00:15:58.970
taking this type of model--

00:15:58.970 --> 00:16:02.490
a more modular approach, more
dynamically loading content.

00:16:02.490 --> 00:16:04.590
And that's really why
we built the bundle.

00:16:04.590 --> 00:16:07.010
That's why we built
that technology.

00:16:07.010 --> 00:16:08.558
And I can't reiterate
that enough.

00:16:08.558 --> 00:16:10.350
I think we've seen a
lot of partners report

00:16:10.350 --> 00:16:13.388
to us how important that's
been for their business.

00:16:13.388 --> 00:16:15.930
I mean, just something so simple
as size reduction can really

00:16:15.930 --> 00:16:17.460
drive that.

00:16:17.460 --> 00:16:20.082
Now, were there any
technical challenges

00:16:20.082 --> 00:16:22.290
that you had to overcome
through that size reduction,

00:16:22.290 --> 00:16:25.170
or through that kind of like
dynamically-loading information

00:16:25.170 --> 00:16:28.172
that maybe you could
share some details on?

00:16:28.172 --> 00:16:29.880
MARK PANELO: In terms
of the actual tech?

00:16:29.880 --> 00:16:30.963
Gosh, I'm not an engineer.

00:16:30.963 --> 00:16:32.710
I really can't tell
you all the details.

00:16:32.710 --> 00:16:36.780
But it was definitely
not an easy process.

00:16:36.780 --> 00:16:38.760
I think the time
that we said we need

00:16:38.760 --> 00:16:40.290
to do this versus
when we actually

00:16:40.290 --> 00:16:42.220
executed was a good six months.

00:16:42.220 --> 00:16:45.030
So I would say if you
guys are starting off

00:16:45.030 --> 00:16:48.960
from a full-package download to
actually changing your strategy

00:16:48.960 --> 00:16:51.390
and doing an initial
download, take some time

00:16:51.390 --> 00:16:52.470
to think through it.

00:16:52.470 --> 00:16:52.680
RAJ AJRAWAT: Yeah.

00:16:52.680 --> 00:16:54.513
And so that's a good
thing to call out, too.

00:16:54.513 --> 00:16:56.640
I think when we have
these conversations

00:16:56.640 --> 00:16:59.430
with our partners,
a lot of times

00:16:59.430 --> 00:17:01.890
it's not just a quick change
that you can put into place.

00:17:01.890 --> 00:17:05.140
This is really an architecture
decision at the end of the day.

00:17:05.140 --> 00:17:06.869
And you kind of have
to leverage a lot

00:17:06.869 --> 00:17:09.079
of resources to
make that happen.

00:17:09.079 --> 00:17:11.520
So that kind of definitely
lines up with a lot of things

00:17:11.520 --> 00:17:13.062
that we're talking
to partners about.

00:17:13.062 --> 00:17:17.910
But I'd like to maybe just take
stock of a lot of these ideas.

00:17:17.910 --> 00:17:22.560
And if you could maybe talk
about one or two things

00:17:22.560 --> 00:17:24.810
that you'd want the
audience to take away from,

00:17:24.810 --> 00:17:28.200
something that we can hopefully
take away as an actionable item

00:17:28.200 --> 00:17:32.040
that they can test back home
with some of their colleagues.

00:17:32.040 --> 00:17:34.140
Jim, maybe we'll start with you.

00:17:34.140 --> 00:17:37.740
What are a few things that
you can talk about that

00:17:37.740 --> 00:17:41.440
if you're trying to prioritize
these items and these tasks?

00:17:41.440 --> 00:17:44.430
What are things they
can do to try and find

00:17:44.430 --> 00:17:46.396
success in these markets?

00:17:46.396 --> 00:17:48.880
JIM STERN: I'd say,
first and foremost,

00:17:48.880 --> 00:17:51.600
if you're looking to do
a game or an application

00:17:51.600 --> 00:17:54.120
in a particular market,
make sure you've really

00:17:54.120 --> 00:17:58.200
done your research to know
what are the traditions there,

00:17:58.200 --> 00:18:03.130
what do people glom
onto, why do they do it.

00:18:03.130 --> 00:18:06.100
The more you can actually have
it built there as well, where

00:18:06.100 --> 00:18:09.960
the people know the traditions,
they know the culture,

00:18:09.960 --> 00:18:10.680
it's much better.

00:18:10.680 --> 00:18:13.470
Because even the subtleties
that they put into the game

00:18:13.470 --> 00:18:16.330
make an incredible difference.

00:18:16.330 --> 00:18:19.260
Same-- like I was talking about
before-- customer service,

00:18:19.260 --> 00:18:20.110
have it there.

00:18:20.110 --> 00:18:22.810
They'll understand how
to talk with the people

00:18:22.810 --> 00:18:25.760
there, how to
communicate with them.

00:18:25.760 --> 00:18:28.020
And I wouldn't just
segment it, I guess,

00:18:28.020 --> 00:18:30.910
to creating an app for
a particular market.

00:18:30.910 --> 00:18:33.630
But if you have
a larger app that

00:18:33.630 --> 00:18:38.790
is global, how do you tap
into those emerging markets?

00:18:38.790 --> 00:18:44.760
And in some cases, it is
customizing events, or sales,

00:18:44.760 --> 00:18:47.280
or whatever it is that you
want to put out to them.

00:18:47.280 --> 00:18:48.810
It will cost a little bit more.

00:18:48.810 --> 00:18:51.000
It will take more
time to put together.

00:18:51.000 --> 00:18:53.640
But they value that,
and they really

00:18:53.640 --> 00:18:56.280
enjoy seeing that they're
an important piece to what's

00:18:56.280 --> 00:18:57.850
going on.

00:18:57.850 --> 00:18:59.920
You can also get into
those emerging markets

00:18:59.920 --> 00:19:00.780
if you're worldwide.

00:19:00.780 --> 00:19:03.210
Because like I was talking
about with liquidity,

00:19:03.210 --> 00:19:04.860
there maybe these
smaller countries

00:19:04.860 --> 00:19:06.670
where you don't have--

00:19:06.670 --> 00:19:10.170
it's not profitable enough for
you to build something just

00:19:10.170 --> 00:19:12.120
for that, but you
can tap into it

00:19:12.120 --> 00:19:14.490
by leveraging all the
rest of the other people.

00:19:14.490 --> 00:19:18.360
So don't just ignore
emerging markets

00:19:18.360 --> 00:19:20.730
because you don't think
you can get into it.

00:19:20.730 --> 00:19:22.230
Leverage everything
else that you're

00:19:22.230 --> 00:19:24.420
doing in terms of the
rest of the world.

00:19:24.420 --> 00:19:25.920
RAJ AJRAWAT: Yeah,
and Mark, I think

00:19:25.920 --> 00:19:28.680
if you could give us maybe a few
things to think about as well.

00:19:28.680 --> 00:19:30.360
MARK PANELO: Yeah, I mean, like
